eft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LA\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Copyright 2017. The New York Times Company. All Rights Reserved. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The nation has split into political tribes. The culture wars are back, waged over transgender rights and immigration. White nationalists are on the march.\par \par \uc2 Amid this turbulence, a surprising group of Americans is testing its moral voice more forcefully than ever: C.E.O.s.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 After Nazi-saluting white supremacists rioted in Charlottesville, Va., and President Trump dithered in his response, a chorus of business leaders rose up this past week to condemn hate groups and espouse tolerance and inclusion. And as lawmakers in Texas tried to restrict the rights of transgender people to use public bathrooms, corporate executives joined activists to kill the bill.\par \par \uc2 These and other actions are part of a broad recasting of the voice of business in the nation\u8217\'20\'19s political and social dialogue, a transformation that has gained momentum in recent years as the country has engaged in fraught debates over everything from {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://topics.nytimes.com/top/news/science/topics/globalwarming/index.html?inline=nyt-classifier"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 climate change}}}\uc2  to health care.\par \par \uc2 In recent days, after the Charlottesville bloodshed, the chief executive of General Motors, \uc2 Mary T. Barra\uc2 , called on people to \u8220\'20\'1Ccome together as a country and reinforce values and ideals that unite us \u8212\'20\'14 tolerance, inclusion and diversity.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Jamie Dimon\uc2  of \uc2 JPMorgan\uc2  said, \u8220\'20\'1CThe equal treatment of all people is one of our nation\u8217\'20\'19s bedrock principles.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Walmart\u8217\'20\'19s chief executive, Doug McMillon, criticized Mr. Trump by name for his handling of the violence in Charlottesville, and called for healing.\par \par \uc2 And in a rebuke to the president, who suggested that both the racist groups and the counterprotesters marching in Charlottesville were to blame for the violence there, a wave of chief executives who had agreed to advise Mr. Trump {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/16/business/trumps-council-ceos.html?mcubz=0"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 quit his business advisory councils}}}\uc2 , leading to the dissolution of two groups.\par \par \uc2 The forthright engagement of these and other executives with one of the most charged political issues in years \u8212\'20\'14 the swelling confidence of a torch-bearing, swastika-saluting, whites-first movement \u8212\'20\'14 is \u8220\'20\'1Ca seminal moment in the history of business in America,\u8221\'20\'1D said Darren Walker, the president of the Ford Foundation and a board member at \uc2 PepsiCo\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CIn this maelstrom, the most clarifying voice has been the voice of business,\u8221\'20\'1D he said. \u8220\'20\'1CThese C.E.O.s have taken the risk to speak truth to power.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 This transformation didn\u8217\'20\'19t happen overnight. Chief executives face a constellation of pressures, and speaking up can create considerable uncertainty. Customers can be offended, colleagues can feel isolated and relations with lawmakers can suffer. Words and actions can backfire, resulting in public relations disasters. All this as a chief executive is expected to constantly grow sales.\par \par \uc2 Even this past week, it was easy to discern careful calculations made by executives who chose to speak out against Mr. Trump. Many faced calls to resign from the presidential advisory councils, and the prospect of boycotts if they did not.\par \par \uc2 But they also faced notable and new kinds of pressure from within \u8212\'20\'14 from employees who expect or encourage their company to stake out positions on numerous controversial social or economic causes, and from board members concerned with reputational issues. In the past week, business leaders have responded with all-staff memos and town-hall meetings.\par \par \uc2 In short, while companies are naturally designed to be moneymaking enterprises, they are adapting to meet new social and political expectations in sometimes startling ways.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CNot every business decision is an economic one,\u8221\'20\'1D said \uc2 Howard Schultz\uc2 , the chairman of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/topic/company/starbucks-corporation?inline=nyt-org"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Starbucks}}}\uc2 , who was one of the country\u8217\'20\'19s first company leaders to proactively address social issues. \u8220\'20\'1CThe reason people are speaking up is that we are fighting for what we love and believe in, and that is the idealism and the aspiration of America, the promise of America, the America that we all know and hold so true.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Looking for Controversy\par \par \uc2 Companies have reckoned with issues of race, class and gender for generations now.\par \par \uc2 On Feb. 1, 1960, four black college students sat down at the segregated lunch counter at a Woolworth\u8217\'20\'19s store in Greensboro, N.C. The civil rights sit-in movement was born, and five months later, Woolworth\u8217\'20\'19s desegregated.\par \par \uc2 Decades later, activists called on American companies to divest from apartheid South Africa. Under pressure, many big companies, including \uc2 General Motors\uc2  and Pepsi, pulled out of the country.\par \par \uc2 But for the most part, companies got political only under duress. Rarely have chief executives gone looking for a controversy. Instead, the prevailing view was one articulated by the economist Milton Friedman {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://query.nytimes.com/mem/archive-free/pdf?res=9E05E0DA153CE531A15750C1A96F9C946190D6CF&mcubz=0"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 in The New York Times}}}\uc2  in 1970: \u8220\'20\'1Cthe social responsibility of business is to increase its profits.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 By the 1990s, some corporate actors began taking the initiative. \uc2 Apple\uc2 , \uc2 Disney\uc2  and \uc2 Xerox\uc2  extended health care benefits to partners of gay and lesbian employees, helping to pave the way for broader acceptance of gay rights. Still, promoting inclusion and advancing diversity were hardly part of the curriculum for emerging titans of industry.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CWhen I went to business school, you didn\u8217\'20\'19t see anything like this,\u8221\'20\'1D said \uc2 Marc Benioff\uc2 , the founder and chief executive of Salesforce. \u8220\'20\'1CNobody talked about taking a stand or adopting a cause.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Now, Mr. Benioff is at the vanguard of a group of executives who are more connected \u8212\'20\'14 to customers, employees, investors and other business leaders \u8212\'20\'14 than ever before, and who are unafraid to use their influence.\par \par \uc2 In 2015, after Indiana passed a law that would have made it easier for religious conservatives to refuse service to gay people, Mr. Benioff {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/28/us/politics/indiana-law-denounced-as-invitation-to-discriminate-against-gays.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 canceled all Salesforce events in the state}}}\uc2  and threatened to relocate employees away from Indianapolis.\par \par \uc2 The outcry from Mr. Benioff and other business leaders helped force politicians, including Vice President \uc2 Mike Pence\uc2 , then the governor of Indiana, to reverse course. Ultimately, lawmakers passed a watered-down version of the law.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CC.E.O.s wield economic influence,\u8221\'20\'1D Mr. Benioff said. \u8220\'20\'1CNobody wanted to lose those jobs in Indiana. But we had to make a statement that we were going to withdraw if they were going to create laws that were going to discriminate against our employees.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 The business community\u8217\'20\'19s triumph in Indiana emboldened progressive executives, and many have become more willing to confront controversial topics unprompted.\par \par \uc2 Randall Stephenson\uc2 , the chief executive of AT&T, recently {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nytimes.com/2016/10/30/business/dealbook/for-att-chief-time-warner-deal-is-the-peak-of-an-ambitious-climb.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 reflected on racial tensions in America}}}\uc2  at a meeting of 2,000 employees. \u8220\'20\'1CBlack lives matter,\u8221\'20\'1D Mr. Stephenson said, \u8220\'20\'1Cwe should not say, \u8216\'20\'18All lives matter,\u8217\'20\'19 to justify ignoring the real need for change.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Hamdi Ulukaya, the founder and chief executive of the yogurt maker Chobani, has hired hundreds of refugees \u8212\'20\'14 {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/01/business/for-helping-immigrants-chobanis-founder-draws-threats.html?_r=0"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 drawing the ire}}}\uc2  of the far right, but making him a cause c\u233\'00\'E9l\u232\'00\'E8bre for progressives.\par \par \uc2 And even before the showdown in Indiana, \uc2 Timothy D. Cook\uc2 , the chief executive of the world\u8217\'20\'19s largest company, \uc2 Apple\uc2 , {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nytimes.com/2014/10/31/technology/timothy-cook-apples-chief-executive-says-he-is-proud-to-be-gay.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 came out as gay}}}\uc2  \u8212\'20\'14 the most prominent executive to make such an announcement. \u8220\'20\'1CI\u8217\'20\'19m proud to be gay, and I consider being gay among the greatest gifts God has given me,\u8221\'20\'1D he wrote.\par \par \uc2 None of this is to say that all corporate leaders are now beacons of morality. The Uber co-founder \uc2 Travis Kalanick\uc2  was ousted amid a mushrooming sexual abuse scandal at the company, and reports that he had cultivated a frat house culture. \uc2 Martin Winterkorn\uc2 , a chief executive of Volkswagen, resigned amid his company\u8217\'20\'19s emissions scandal.\par \par \uc2 But faced with circumstances they cannot in good conscience accept, more and more chieftains appear unafraid to act. In June, after the president withdrew the United States from the Paris climate accord, \uc2 Elon Musk\uc2 , the chief executive of Tesla, and \uc2 Robert A. Iger\uc2 , the chief of \uc2 Disney\uc2 , resigned from presidential advisory councils, setting the stage for this past week\u8217\'20\'19s revolt.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThe C.E.O.s of big public companies don\u8217\'20\'19t walk out onto the plank of social and political leadership by default,\u8221\'20\'1D said Nancy Koehn, a historian at Harvard Business School. \u8220\'20\'1CBut today, to keep silent is to jeopardize the reputation of the company.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8216\'20\'18Many Sides,\u8217\'20\'19 One Voice\par \par \uc2 Last weekend, as white nationalists protested the removal of a statue of the Confederate general Robert E. Lee in Charlottesville, chief executives were paying close attention to the president\u8217\'20\'19s response. Among those watching was \uc2 Kenneth C. Frazier\uc2 , the chief executive of the drugmaker Merck and one of dozens of executives who had agreed to advise Mr. Trump on economic issues.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Frazier disagreed with the president\u8217\'20\'19s stances on immigration and climate change, but he believed it was important to have a seat at the table. Yet for Mr. Frazier, the son of a janitor and the grandson of a man born into slavery, the president\u8217\'20\'19s remarks \u8212\'20\'14 in which he blamed the violence on \u8220\'20\'1Cmany sides\u8221\'20\'1D \u8212\'20\'14 were too much to bear.\par \par \uc2 On Monday morning, Mr. Frazier said he would step down from Mr. Trump\u8217\'20\'19s manufacturing council. \u8220\'20\'1CAs C.E.O. of Merck and as a matter of personal conscience, I feel a responsibility to take a stand against intolerance and extremism,\u8221\'20\'1D he wrote.\par \par \uc2 The president took to Twitter, lacerating Mr. Frazier and attacking Merck, bluster that alienated more chief executives. By the end of the day, the chiefs of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/topic/company/under-armour-inc?inline=nyt-org"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Under Armour}}}\uc2  and \uc2 Intel\uc2  had dropped off the same advisory group. The following morning, three nonprofit business leaders also quit.\par \par \uc2 As the manufacturing council fell apart, another presidential advisory group was also tottering. The Strategic and Policy Forum, a group with chief executives of some of the country\u8217\'20\'19s biggest companies, held a conference call and agreed to disband.\par \par \uc2 The reaction from business leaders extended well beyond the confines of the presidential advisory councils.\par \par \uc2 James Murdoch\uc2 , the chief executive of 21st Century Fox, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/17/us/politics/james-murdoch-trump-donation-anti-defamation-league.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 pledged to donate}}}\uc2  $1 million to the \uc2 Anti-Defamation League\uc2 . The gesture was all the more remarkable because Mr. Murdoch is the son of \uc2 Rupert Murdoch\uc2 , a staunch supporter of Mr. Trump, and because his company operates Fox News, known for its favorable coverage of the president.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CWhat we watched this last week in Charlottesville and the reaction to it by the President of the United States concern all of us as Americans and free people,\u8221\'20\'1D the younger Mr. Murdoch wrote in an email to associates. \u8220\'20\'1CI can\u8217\'20\'19t even believe I have to write this: standing up to Nazis is essential; there are no good Nazis. Or Klansmen, or terrorists.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Technology companies {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://qz.com/1055141/what-websites-and-apps-have-banned-neo-nazis-and-white-supremacists/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 severed ties}}}\uc2  with white supremacist groups. \uc2 Google\uc2  and GoDaddy dropped domain registrations for far right publications. \uc2 Facebook\uc2  deleted articles that celebrated hate crimes. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/17/business/media/white-power-rock-bands-find-platform-online-to-incite-hatred.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Spotify took down music}}}\uc2  by white power rock bands.\par \par \uc2 And in Seattle, Mr. Schultz {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://news.starbucks.com/news/hate-has-no-home-here"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 held a town-hall meeting}}}\uc2  for more than 1,000 employees where he condemned bigotry and called for unity. \u8220\'20\'1CI could sense the anxiety,\u8221\'20\'1D he said. \u8220\'20\'1CI felt a need to create a safe and loving \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 All week, the business world\u8217\'20\'19s actions went beyond the donations to charity and pledges to plant trees that once defined \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CFor a long time, \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  was a buzzword marketing tool, walled off within an organization,\u8221\'20\'1D said Alan Fleischmann, president of Laurel Strategies, an executive advisory firm. \u8220\'20\'1CNow it has to be central for the C.E.O., part of their everyday responsibility and leadership.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 The Cost of Speaking Out\par \par \uc2 Kevin Plank\uc2 , the founder and chief executive of Under Armour, the athletic apparel maker, built a brand that celebrates diversity, sponsoring athletes like the basketball player Stephen Curry and artists like the ballerina Misty Copeland. Yet when asked to serve on the president\u8217\'20\'19s manufacturing council early this year, Mr. Plank agreed, voicing his optimism about Mr. Trump.\par \par \uc2 His star sponsors made their displeasure known. \u8220\'20\'1CI strongly disagree with \uc2 Kevin Plank\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s recent comments in support of Trump,\u8221\'20\'1D Ms. Copeland said. Mr. Curry also expressed his distaste for the president.\par \par \uc2 So on Monday night, when Mr. Plank stepped down from his advisory role, he might have thought his troubles were over. Instead, Mr. Trump\u8217\'20\'19s supporters have risen up, calling for a boycott of \uc2 Under Armour\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThe leaders of corporate America have demonstrated the courage to call out something that is unacceptable,\u8221\'20\'1D said Mr. Walker of the \uc2 Ford Foundation\uc2 . \u8220\'20\'1CBut speaking truth to power can come with huge costs.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Because companies have inherently diverse customers and employees, taking a stand can be a no-win situation for chief executives. For every employee, investor and customer they make happy, they may well make someone else unhappy.\par \par \uc2 When Pepsi this year released an ad featuring Kendall Jenner offering a police officer a soda in the midst of an apparent Black Lives Matter protest, the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/05/business/kendall-jenner-pepsi-ad.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 condemnation was swift}}}\uc2 . Two years earlier, \uc2 Starbucks{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/23/business/media/starbucks-ends-tempestuous-initiative-on-race.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 drew wide ridicule}}}\uc2  when, as part of an effort by Mr. Schultz to start a national conversation on race relations, baristas were encouraged to write \u8220\'20\'1Crace together\u8221\'20\'1D on coffee cups.\par \par \uc2 Companies on the conservative end of the ideological spectrum are also increasingly willing to stand up for their principles, and just as likely to face criticism. After it was revealed that the family behind the fast-food chain \uc2 Chick-fil-A\uc2  supported groups that opposed same-sex marriage, gay rights protesters {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.nytimes.com/2012/07/26/us/gay-rights-uproar-over-chick-fil-a-widens.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 targeted the restaurants}}}\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Hobby Lobby, the craft-supply chain run by a conservative Christian family, challenged a provision in the Affordable Care Act that required family-owned corporations to pay for insurance coverage for birth control. Despite drawing the ire of the left, Hobby Lobby {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/01/us/hobby-lobby-case-supreme-court-contraception.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 took its case to the Supreme Court}}}\uc2  and won.\par \par \uc2 Critics of Mr. Plank\u8217\'20\'19s decision cast their net wide, going after all the chief executives who quit the president\u8217\'20\'19s business advisory groups. \u8220\'20\'1CThis is a remarkable moment in history,\u8221\'20\'1D {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=d_RR8zFJJdU"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 said Lou Dobbs}}}\uc2 , a \uc2 Fox Business Network\uc2  host. \u8220\'20\'1CEvery one of those C.E.O.s, mark my words, is a coward \u8212\'20\'14 and the president is exactly right \u8212\'20\'14 a grandstander in the service of the left. And no one should make any mistake: This is a coordinated, orchestrated attack against this president.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 John Carney\uc2 , a business editor for Breitbart News, the conservative news site, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.breitbart.com/big-government/2017/08/17/corporate-antifa-ceos-revolt-against-american-democracy/"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 wrote that}}}\uc2  \u8220\'20\'1Ccorporate America is part of the opposition.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThe confederacy of the media institutions, the American left, and Corporate America has aligned itself against the populist uprising that brought Trump to the White House,\u8221\'20\'1D Mr. Carney wrote. \u8220\'20\'1CThe battle lines are clear.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Those executives who go out on a limb know the risks. \u8220\'20\'1CWe all recognize that with every decision we make, there is a group of people that are not going to agree with us,\u8221\'20\'1D Mr. Schultz said. \u8220\'20\'1CBut you must define your core purpose for being. We stand in the interest of something greater than just making money.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 A Diversity Paradox\par \par \uc2 Diversity \u8212\'20\'14 of opinions, ideologies and religions \u8212\'20\'14 is what makes taking a stand on moral issues so treacherous for C.E.O.s. Yet paradoxically, it is also diversity \u8212\'20\'14 of races, genders and worldviews, among customers and the work force \u8212\'20\'14 that makes many of the executives, when forced to take a stand, come down on the side of inclusion, tolerance and acceptance.\par \par \uc2 Business leaders looking to the future are accepting that it is unwise to isolate swaths of the population by coming off as racist, sexist or intolerant. Instead, for the sake of the bottom line, it is imperative that they appeal to the widest possible audience. \u8220\'20\'1CBusiness leaders aren\u8217\'20\'19t threatened by an America that is browner, an America that is more diverse; they welcome that,\u8221\'20\'1D Mr. Walker said. \u8220\'20\'1CBusiness leaders are bullish on diversity.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 What\u8217\'20\'19s more, some executives have concluded that speaking out on issues of morality can improve more than their reputations \u8212\'20\'14 it can benefit recruitment, morale and even sales. \u8220\'20\'1COur employees come here knowing that this is something that is extremely important to us,\u8221\'20\'1D said Mr. Benioff of \uc2 Salesforce\uc2 . \u8220\'20\'1CBusiness is the greatest platform for affecting change.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 If the voices of business leaders seem amplified, that is perhaps because in such partisan times, few politicians can speak to both sides of the aisle, leaving a vacuum for business leaders to fill. This last week, the executives on Mr. Trump\u8217\'20\'19s business advisory councils piped up, led by Mr. Frazier of Merck.\par \par \uc2 The black chief executive of a $172 billion company \u8212\'20\'14 a multimillionaire who was born in a poor neighborhood, a former lawyer who fought for civil rights and had agreed to advise the president \u8212\'20\'14 Mr. Frazier offered remarks that set the tone for the business world at large.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1COur country\u8217\'20\'19s strength stems from its diversity,\u8221\'20\'1D he wrote, adding, \u8220\'20\'1CAmerica\u8217\'20\'19s leaders must honor our fundamental values by clearly rejecting expressions of hatred, bigotry and group supremacy, which run counter to the American ideal that all people are created equal.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 The C.E.O.s had found their voice.\par \par \uc2 Follow David Gelles on Twitter @dgelles.\par \par \uc2 * {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/16/business/trumps-council-ceos.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Inside the C.E.O. Rebellion Against Trump\u8217\'20\'19s Advisory Councils}}}\par \par \uc2 * {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/14/business/merck-ceo-trump-charlottesville.html"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Under Armour and Intel C.E.O.s Follow Merck Chief, Quitting Panel in Rebuke to Trump}}}\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b ART\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Minh Uong/The New York Times \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \