voluntarily\u160\'00\'A0reducing its greenhouse gas emissions. And an outdoor apparel and gear seller named Cotopaxi is training Sudanese refugees in Utah to be computer programmers.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 They were among the companies showcased at the \uc2 U. S. Chamber of Commerce Foundation\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s fourth annual corporate citizenship conference last week, titled "Opportunity Forward. " Although the current administration's policies weren\u8217\'20\'19t explicitly discussed, they loomed large in the backdrop.\par \par \uc2 More: Business, community groups boost health partnerships\par \par \uc2 More: COKER: Use \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  to build trust, not as marketing ploy\par \par \uc2 More: Businesses, governments boost workforce health\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThe planet is screwed,\u8221\'20\'1D Neil Gaugh, founder of British corporate consulting firm Neil Gaugh & Associates, said of global warming at the opening session of Wednesday\u8217\'20\'19s program. \u8220\'20\'1CWe are aware this is a problem. A lot of people are looking to businesses to solve the problem. \u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Gaugh and other speakers cited a growing realization among corporations that helping others is good for business and should be part and parcel of a company\u8217\'20\'19s core mission, not relegated to a must-do list.\par \par \uc2 Social and economic goals \u8220\'20\'1Ccan be combined into one thing,\u8221\'20\'1D Gaugh\u160\'00\'A0told an audience of about 500 at the Ronald Reagan Building and International Trade Center. He also issued\u160\'00\'A0a warning to companies that don\u8217\'20\'19t embrace corporate citizenship authentically.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThe days of hiding behind your brand are over,\u8221\'20\'1D he said, comparing such efforts to putting lipstick on a gorilla - an image that promptly appeared on a large screen.\par \par \uc2 Gaugh said he once worked at BP and was involved in the oil giant's efforts to burnish its\u160\'00\'A0image on the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  with the \u8220\'20\'1CBeyond Petroleum\u8221\'20\'1D ad campaign. But it was undermined\u160\'00\'A0by company accidents in Texas in 2005, Alaska in 2006 and the Gulf of Mexico in 2010.\par \par \uc2 Today, BP\u160\'00\'A0is working to balance its commitment to shareholders and what it sees as its responsibility to help ensure a future where power is generated in a way that meaningfully reduces the amount of carbon dioxide emitted from conventional fossil fuel energy production. \u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 "For all companies, especially publicly traded we\u8217\'20\'19ve got this quarterly demand for results and performance and that certainly drives the day-to-day thinking often, but we also recognize there is this real long term we have the responsibility to contribute towards, " said Ray Dempsey Jr. chief diversity officer at BP America and president of the BP Foundation in a separate session. "So in this lower carbon-energy future, our commitment is to provide the world\u8217\'20\'19s energy needs today - in whatever forms those are -\u160\'00\'A0\u160\'00\'A0and prepare for this lower carbon energy future, and we must do both. It\u8217\'20\'19s not a tradeoff\u160\'00\'A0. . . It\u8217\'20\'19s not a one or the other. We must do both and we must do it in a way that it meets the obligations to society to keep the lights and the power and the vehicles moving today and make sure we have the opportunity to still do that for generations to come. "\par \par \uc2 During the conference, a parade of company executives took the stage to describe how their \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 \u160\'00\'A0programs\u160\'00\'A0arose from personal experiences\u160\'00\'A0that sparked heartfelt commitments.\par \par \uc2 Chieh Huang, CEO of Boxed, an online retailer of bulk items, says he was inspired\u160\'00\'A0at an employee appreciation event when a box loaderwho had been laid off from another job in 2008 told him he had never before been honored in a corporate \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Huang said he realized, \u8220\'20\'1CWe were shepherding folks who had their entire livelihood in our hands. \u8221\'20\'1D He vowed, \u8220\'20\'1CWe will never let you down. \u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 The New York City-based company helps pay the college tuition of workers\u8217\'20\'19 kids. And after an\u160\'00\'A0employee said he couldn\u8217\'20\'19t afford a wedding, Huang decided to offer staffers generous wedding stipends and unlimited vacations. Boxed also gives consumers rebates for what Huang\u160\'00\'A0considers unfair taxes on feminine hygiene products-often referred to as the "Pink Tax. "\par \par \uc2 Stephan Jacob, co-founder Cotopaxi, decided to weave citizenship into the company\u8217\'20\'19s mission because his earlier efforts at a nonprofit were chronically underfunded. Besides donating 2% of Cotopaxi\u8217\'20\'19s revenue to \u8220\'20\'1Chealth, education and livelihood\u8221\'20\'1D causes, the company, based in Salt Lake City, uses llama wool to make some clothing\u160\'00\'A0to help Bolivian llama farmers. It asks company software engineers to train refugees from Sudan and other countries to be software programmers. And to cut landfill waste, it uses excess materials from other backpack makers to produce a line of patchwork backpacks that is among its most popular. \u8220\'20\'1CYou can do good and do well economically at the same time,\u8221\'20\'1D he said. \u160\'00\'A0\par \par \uc2 Other corporate efforts:\par \par \uc2 \u8226\'20\'22 Life is Good, which makes T-shirts with that and other upbeat slogans, channels 10% of its profits to its children\u8217\'20\'19s foundation. And it connects people inspired by its messages on social media. If a job applicant doesn\u8217\'20\'19t commit to its philosophy of spreading optimism, \u8220\'20\'1CWe don\u8217\'20\'19t want you,\u8221\'20\'1D said company president Lisa Tanzer.\par \par \uc2 \u8226\'20\'22 In their\u160\'00\'A0home base in Atlanta, \uc2 Chick-fil-A\uc2  executives\u160\'00\'A0grew weary of seeing rampant poverty and blight in the Northside Drive neighborhood, which\u160\'00\'A0sits in the shadows of\u160\'00\'A0one of the nation\u8217\'20\'19s top corporate hubs. \u8220\'20\'1CWe said, \u8216\'20\'18We can do better than this,\u8217\'20\'19\u8221\'20\'1D said Rodney Bullard, the company\u8217\'20\'19s vice president of community affairs. So it\u8217\'20\'19s donating $20 million to revitalize the area while striving to keep many residents there. It also plans to build\u160\'00\'A0a restaurant in the neighborhood to lure other businesses even though it\u8217\'20\'19s not currently financially viable.\par \par \uc2 \u8226\'20\'22 \uc2 Entergy\uc2  is reducing its carbon emissions to 2000 levels, said Patty Riddlebarger, director of \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 . She said the effort has attracted investors who seek out environmentally responsible utilities. \u8220\'20\'1CWe found that it\u8217\'20\'19s a significant competitive advantage,\u8221\'20\'1D she said.\par \par \uc2 \u160\'00\'A0\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15