n0\lin0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Copyright 2018 Dow Jones & Company, Inc. All Rights Reserved. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 In "{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.wsj.com/articles/stocks-werent-made-for-social-climbing-1516565984"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Stocks Weren't Made for Social Climbing}}}\uc2 " (Inside View, Jan. 22), Andy Kessler expresses concern that "\b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 " (CSR) funds have failed to keep pace with the S&P 500 Index. He's right. Over the 10 years ending 2017, annual returns on the average large-cap CSR fund were 7.8%, trailing the 8.5% return of the S&P 500 by 0.7%. But actively managed large-cap funds that don't consider CSR issues performed even worse, earning 7.7% per year and trailing the index by 0.8%. There may be valid objections to CSR funds, but over the past decade they've performed slightly better than their non-CSR peers. The S&P 500 remains a tough standard for all active managers to outpace.\par \par \uc2 John C. Bogle\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Valley Forge, Pa.\par \par \uc2 "Social investing" campaigns include not only promotion of preferred investments but a determined effort to disable these investments' competition. That darker flip side involves a "climate risk disclosure" industry. Players in this "CRD" movement include state attorneys general, comptrollers and treasurers, and lawmakers combining with public pension funds, interest groups and, of course, contingency-fee lawyers. Even academics admit to expecting a taste of the expected settlement fund.\par \par \uc2 The campaign seeks to impede access to capital\u8212\'20\'14one player called it "divestment through value destruction." The effective goal is to coerce "confessions" in energy-related interests' public filings that catastrophic man-made global warming is a real problem of which they constitute a significant part, that their reserves are in fact worth little to nothing and their previous filings and other statements constitute actionable misdeeds, possibly fraud.\par \par \uc2 The "social investing" industry represents more than suspect fiscal responsibility. It also embodies the darker attributes of the climate and environmental industries.\par \par \uc2 Chris Horner\par \par \uc2 Energy & \b \highlight22\uc2 Environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  Legal Institute\par \par \uc2 Washington\par \par \uc2 Investors focused on profits regularly stop investing in companies that are underperforming the market\u8212\'20\'14particularly when those companies produce products the global community has concluded threaten humanity. It was financially rational to stop investing in coal companies, the worst climate polluters, long before the leading companies went bankrupt. Like coal a few years back, oil and gas stocks have been underperforming the market for the last five years. For example, while the S&P 500 was up more than 80%, \uc2 Exxon Mobil\uc2  was down 6%. Where's the profit maximizing there? Moreover, the recent rise in oil prices Mr. Kessler notes has done little to lift oil stock prices. Besides, the \uc2 Rockefeller Family Fund\uc2  is a long-term investor and keeps its eye on the horizon.\par \par \uc2 Advocates of pure profit maximizing claim it best allocates resources, but they ignore externalities. Mr. Kessler therefore misses the simplest reason to unload oil and gas stocks. They have been woefully underperforming in the market and appear likely to continue to do so.\par \par \uc2 Lee Wasserman\par \par \uc2 Director, \uc2 Rockefeller Family Fund\par \par \uc2 New York\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 ccsr : \uc2 Corporate Social Responsibility | nlet : \uc2 Letters | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | ncat : \uc2 Content Types | nfact : \uc2 Factiva Filters | nfce : \uc2 C&E Exclusion Filter | nfcpex : \uc2 C&E Executive News Filter | niwe : \uc2 IWE Filter | nrgn : \uc2 Routine General News\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15