 and stick saves -- though these are nothing, really, next to the most audacious save on which the \uc2 NHL\uc2  has set its sights:\par \par \uc2 Save the planet.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 That may sound like a joke. What does hockey have to do with environmental policy? Well, for one thing, the game is played on ice. And frozen ponds, where so many of the league's players learned to skate, are in trouble. The average length of the skating season may shrink by one-third in eastern Canada and by 20% in western Canada in coming decades.\par \par \uc2 That's according to research in the \uc2 NHL\uc2 's 2018 sustainability report, out Wednesday morning. The report assesses the league's own environmental impact and its commitment to fighting climate change.\par \par \uc2 Allen Hershkowitz, founding director and chairman of the Board of Sport and Sustainability International, credits the \uc2 NHL\uc2  for using that term -- "climate change" -- after the Trump administration announced in June that the U.S. would walk away from the 195-nation Paris climate accord and Environmental Protection Agency Administrator Scott Pruitt said carbon dioxide is not a primary contributor to global warming.\par \par \uc2 "It would be dishonest not to acknowledge that the report is coming out when the world is facing the most challenging political climate in the United States as it relates to climate change policies," says Hershkowitz, whose non-governmental organization has members in more than 50 countries.\par \par \uc2 Leagues prefer to stay far away from controversy so they don't alienate fans. Just look at the \uc2 NFL\uc2 , where players kneeling for the national anthem last season caused considerable outcry.\par \par \uc2 Hershkowitz says climate change is about science, not politics. Even so, does the \uc2 NHL\uc2  worry about disaffecting fans who may think otherwise?\par \par \uc2 "What I would say is, when we do this work, we try to do it as apolitically as possible," says Omar Mitchell, NHL vice president for \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 . "Because at the end of the day, as our commissioner would say, this is the right thing to do."\par \par \uc2 More than a dozen federal agencies issued a report late last year that said humans are the dominant cause of a rise in global temperatures that has led to the warmest period in the history of civilization. That report said global average temperatures have increased 1.8 degrees Fahrenheit over the past 115 years.\par \par \uc2 That's a period of time that encompasses the rise of hockey. The \uc2 NHL\uc2  celebrated its centennial in 2017 -- and it wants to be around for its bicentennial.\par \par \uc2 "How we think about our \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and how we think about sustainability is going to be a critical element in making sure our sport has a future," says Kim Davis, NHL executive vice president of social impact, growth initiatives and legislative affairs.\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 NHL\uc2 's report is voluntary. "And what gives the report its teeth is that we did a carbon inventory" of the league's own environmental impact, Mitchell says. "Hockey is a very energy-intensive sport. Our analysis shows about 66% of our carbon footprint is attributed to energy usage to create an ice sheet. So what we are trying to do is to promote innovations that will lower energy consumption within our buildings."\par \par \uc2 The league launched its \uc2 NHL\uc2  Green initiative in 2010 and released its first sustainability report in 2014. Among highlights of this second report:\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 NHL\uc2  reduced energy consumption 1% from fiscal year 2014 to fiscal year 2016.\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 NHL\uc2  decreased water consumption 7% from fiscal year 2015 to fiscal year 2016.\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 NHL\uc2  reduced CO2 emissions by 2% year-over-year from fiscal year 2014 to fiscal year 2016.\par \par \uc2 "The single most important thing the \uc2 NHL\uc2  has done is measure, and refine the measurement protocol, for professional sports," Hershkowitz says. "It can't be understated how important that is, (measuring) energy use, water use and waste generation at arenas that you don't own and that you occupy for only a fraction of the time."\par \par \uc2 Scott Jenkins is general manager of Mercedes-Benz Stadium in Atlanta and chairman of the Green Sports Alliance, which includes nearly 500 sports teams and venues from 15 sports leagues in 14 countries. He says sports teams are in favorable positions to influence the broader culture on environmental concerns and to show that being environmentally sensitive is good for business.\par \par \uc2 "We can't afford to live on the sidelines," Jenkins says. "We have to get in the game."\par \par \uc2 Which brings us back to frozen ponds. The \uc2 NHL\uc2 's sustainability report tells of RinkWatch, which encourages citizens to monitor outdoor rinks and ponds in their neighborhoods. The initiative was launched by researchers at \uc2 Wilfrid Laurier University\uc2  in Waterloo, Ontario, in 2013. More than 1,400 rinks and ponds are tracked to help scientists study the long-term effects of climate change.\par \par \uc2 "If you trace (hockey) back to the sort of humble beginnings, particularly in Canada, it all goes back to frozen ponds," Davis says. "A lot of NHL players grew up playing hockey outdoors. It's such a critical part of the game, and it's important that access remains available for future generations."\par \par \uc2 CREDIT: Erik Brady, \uc2 USA TODAY\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 giceh : \uc2 Ice Hockey | gclimt : \uc2 Climate Change | gsporg : \uc2 Sports Organizations | c151 : \uc2 Earnings | e1105 : \uc2 Consumer Sentiment | ecat : \uc2 Economic News | genv : \uc2 Natural Environment | ghock : \uc2 Field Hockey | gsust : \uc2 Sustainable Development | gwere : \uc2 Routine Weather Reports | npag : \uc2 Page-One Stories | c15 : \uc2 Financial Performance | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | e11 : \uc2 Economic Performance/Indicators | gcat : \uc2 Political/General News | gglobe : \uc2 Global/World Issues | gspo : \uc2 Sports | gwea : \uc2 Weather | gwint : \uc2 Winter Sports | ncat : \uc2 Content Types | nfact : \uc2 Factiva Filters | nfce : \uc2 C&E Exclusion Filter | nfcpin : \uc2 C&E Industry News Filter | nrgn : \uc2 Routine General News\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RE\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 cana : \uc2 Canada | namz : \uc2 North America\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \c