ha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 WSJO\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LA\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Copyright 2018 Dow Jones & Company, Inc. All Rights Reserved. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 If you can't beat them, join them\u8212\'20\'14or at least steal their script.\par \par \uc2 Justin Danhof a conservative shareholder advocate, is harnessing a regulatory "first-come, first-served" provision to sideline left-leaning investors from proxy ballots by lodging nearly identical proposals, but getting them in first. The tactic is helping Mr. Danhof promote and engage with company management on conservative social-policy issues.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Mr. Danhof, who decided to take advantage of the regulatory quirk last summer, worked to submit a shareholder proposal in November demanding \uc2 General Electric Co\uc2 . divulge more information about its lobbying expenditures.\par \par \uc2 The conservative advocate's documents arrived at GE on Nov. 6. A nearly identical proposal from the \uc2 New York State Common Retirement Fund\uc2  arrived two days later.\par \par \uc2 The statements supporting the two resolutions were polar opposites. Mr. Danhof said GE need not hide its contributions because it should "be proud of its membership in trade associations\u8230\'20\'26that promote pro-business, pro-growth initiatives."\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, the New York state fund called for greater transparency on such spending so shareholders can "fully evaluate the political use of corporate assets."\par \par \uc2 Securities rules meant Mr. Danhof's proposal made it to the company's 2018 proxy, which goes to vote on April 25, and beat out New York's nearly identical version.\par \par \uc2 A company can ask the \uc2 Securities and Exchange Commission\uc2  to exclude a resolution from its ballot if it is "substantially duplicative" of a proposal submitted earlier by another shareholder. That was the case with GE, which petitioned the regulator to exclude the state's proposal.\par \par \uc2 "I knew the liberals were going to file their resolution blasting membership [in certain trade and lobby groups]\u8230\'20\'26so I filed a resolution with the same language," said Mr. Danhof, general counsel at the National Center for Public Policy Research. The conservative research and communications foundation is one of a handful of right-leaning organizations using shareholder resolutions.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Danhof's strategy for the 2018 proxy season is to make the best use of this new tactic: Submit the same proposal as a left-leaning shareholder, but get it in first.\par \par \uc2 Investors have long relied on shareholder resolutions\u8212\'20\'14proposed by some stock owners and included in a company's proxy for a vote by all shareholders\u8212\'20\'14to wring greater accountability from boards.\par \par \uc2 Shareholders filed 1,347 resolutions focused on social policy and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  with Fortune 250 companies in the decade ended in 2015, according to ProxyMonitor.org.\par \par \uc2 None of them garnered majority shareholder support.\par \par \uc2 That's starting to change. A proposal seeking greater disclosure of political spending by \uc2 Fluor Corp\uc2 . passed in 2016. And last year, fund managers BlackRock Inc. and \uc2 Vanguard Group\uc2  voted with the proponents of climate-risk disclosure at \uc2 Exxon Mobil Corp\uc2 . and \uc2 Occidental Petroleum Corp\uc2 . among others.\par \par \uc2 "The comfort level in a boardroom changes when you get large global investors supporting or even voting for an environmental resolution," said Timothy Smith, director of shareholder engagement at \uc2 Walden Asset Management\uc2 , a $3.6 billion sustainable-investments fund.\par \par \uc2 The shift spurred Mr. Danhof to take up shareholder resolutions with new gusto.\par \par \uc2 "Every other group that engages with corporations on social policy is liberal," he said. "They are pushing a very far-left agenda."\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 National Center\uc2 , a 35-year-old Washington-based organization, submits 15 to 25 proposals each year on issues such as freedom of speech, freedom of association, and corporate charitable contributions.\par \par \uc2 This isn't the first time Mr. Danhof got a proposal on GE's proxy. Last year, he requested the company disclose its charitable contributions, citing concerns over reports that GE had donated to \uc2 the Clinton Foundation\uc2  and Planned Parenthood. GE declined to comment.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Danhof's latest GE proposal dealt a setback to New York State Comptroller Thomas DiNapoli, who has emphasized environmental, social and governance issues as trustee of the Common Retirement Fund.\par \par \uc2 "It's questionable whether these shadow proposals share the same sincerity and concern for managing risk to investors' portfolios or are merely cynical attempts to sideline legitimate shareholder proposals," Mr. DiNapoli said in a emailed statement.\par \par \uc2 The fund is the third-largest public pension fund in the U.S., with $209 billion under management, and will look to file its proposals earlier next year, a spokesman said.\par \par \uc2 Proposals, even those that failed to get on the proxy, have led to increased dialogue between companies and shareholders in recent years as submissions on environmental and social issues grew, said governance experts at law firm Cleary Gottlieb.\par \par \uc2 The swing toward greater shareholder engagement has worked for Mr. Danhof. A campaign to ensure employees' rights to private political activity led to greater protections at 13 companies, he said.\par \par \uc2 "Filing a proposal is an opening, to encourage discussion, and it can lead to truthful negotiations to advance the issues we're focused on," he said.\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 National Center\uc2  filed a lobbying-expenditures proposal with \uc2 Duke Energy Corp\uc2 . on Nov. 16. A day later, a virtually identical proposal arrived from a social-investing group, the Sisters of St. Francis of Philadelphia.\par \par \uc2 The group intends to vote agains